# Trading Intelligence Platform — Core Principles

## Architecture Boundaries
- `apps/web` (Next.js) MUST NOT import from `apps/api` and MUST NOT use Prisma directly.
- Frontend ↔ backend communicate over HTTP only. The only shared code is typed contracts (e.g. `packages/contracts` or a generated client).
- Business logic lives in `apps/api` services. Controllers orchestrate; services decide; repositories persist.

## MVP Phase Discipline
- Current phase: **paper trading + dashboards + automation**. No live broker code.
- Broker integration is behind a `BrokerPort` interface with a `PaperBroker` default. A real `AlpacaBroker` is stubbed until explicitly scheduled.
- No queues, microservices, event sourcing, or multi-tenant plumbing unless a concrete user story in the current phase needs it.

## Simplicity Rules
- Explicit > clever. No premature DRY, no speculative abstractions, no "utils" dumping grounds.
- A function beats a class when there is no state. A module beats a package when it isn't reused.
- New dependency requires a one-line justification and a simpler alternative considered.

## Money & Time
- Money is never `float` / `number`. Use Prisma `Decimal` in persistence and integer cents or `Decimal.js` in memory. Format only at the UI edge.
- All timestamps are UTC `DateTime`. No local time in storage or on the wire.

## Type Safety
- No `any` in public signatures. No `@ts-ignore` without an inline comment explaining why.
- Parse untrusted input at the boundary (DTO or zod). Internal code trusts its types.

## Definition of Done
- Typecheck, lint, and tests are green.
- New backend logic has at least one unit or integration test.
- Behavior changes are visible in a commit message or PR description — not only in code.
